DRC President Joseph Kabila. (AFP) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Kinshasa - A rights group says the Democratic Republic of Congo security forces have killed at least 34 people amid protests in in that country against President Joseph Kabila's extended rule, as mediators urge the ruling and opposition parties to find a way out of the political crisis.Human Rights Watch researcher Ida Sawyer said on Thursday the group has confirmed the deaths in several cities, and the toll is likely to climb. She also told Radio France International that security forces are targeting both protesters and passers-by.Kabila's constitutional mandate ended this week. A court has ruled he can remain in power until a new leader is elected. November elections have been postponed indefinitely.Catholic church-led mediations continued Thursday morning.Police say the heavy security presence will be maintained through the holidays.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.